<subSubSection lastPageId="76" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="75.[151,1437,1862,2031]" lastBlockId="76.[151,1437,151,758]" lastPageId="76" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1934,1959]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Description</emphasis>
. 
<typeStatus box="[360,464,1934,1959]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Holotype</typeStatus>
complete (
<collectingRegion box="[606,693,1935,1959]" country="Ireland" name="Monaghan" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
<collectionCode box="[606,693,1935,1959]" country="France" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" name="Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">MNHN</collectionCode>
</collectingRegion>
IA-Type 1798), broken into two pieces (
<figureCitation box="[1211,1324,1934,1959]" captionStart="FIGURE 39" captionStartId="76.[151,250,1707,1729]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,809,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@76.[172,1419,809,1664]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="FIGURE 39. Bradabyssa monnioti n. sp., holotype (MNHN IA-Type 1798). A. Dorsal view. B. Chaetiger 10, left parapodium, anterior view. C. Same, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. D. Same, basal, medial and distal neurochaetal regions. Scale bars. A: 0.5 mm, B: 90 µm, C – D: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041288/files/figure.png" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Fig. 39A</figureCitation>
), slightly damaged, integument with three transverse ridges, especially along anterior body half, whitish with dark fine sediment particles remaining basally in lateral papillae. Body cylindrical, blunt anteriorly, tapered posteriorly, 
<quantity lastPageId="76" lastPageNumber="77" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.8" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" unit="mm" value="7.8">7.8 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[273,363,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
wide, cephalic cage 
<quantity box="[612,702,151,176]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
long, 29 chaetigers. Tunic papillated, papillae sparse (eroded), cylindrical, very long, basally with adherent fine sediment particles. Posterior end papillae very long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1437,151,758]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Anterior end not exposed; not dissected to avoid further damage. Cephalic cage chaetae as long as 1/15 body length, or about ¼ body width. Chaetiger 1 involved in cephalic cage; chaetae arranged in short lateral series; 2 notochaetae and 3 neurochaetae per fascicle.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1437,151,758]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Anterior dorsal margin of first chaetiger papillated, not projecting anteriorly. Chaetigers 1–3 of similar length. Chaetal transition from cephalic cage to body chaetae abrupt; small aristate neurospines present from chaetiger 2. Gonopodial lobes in chaetiger 5.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1437,151,758]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
Parapodia poorly developed, chaetae emerge from body wall (
<figureCitation box="[895,998,445,470]" captionStart="FIGURE 39" captionStartId="76.[151,250,1707,1729]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,809,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@76.[172,1419,809,1664]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="FIGURE 39. Bradabyssa monnioti n. sp., holotype (MNHN IA-Type 1798). A. Dorsal view. B. Chaetiger 10, left parapodium, anterior view. C. Same, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. D. Same, basal, medial and distal neurochaetal regions. Scale bars. A: 0.5 mm, B: 90 µm, C – D: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041288/files/figure.png" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Fig. 39B</figureCitation>
). Parapodia lateral; median neuropodia ventrolateral. Notopodia and neuropodia close to each other; short low conical lobes, neuropodial ones larger.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1437,151,758]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
Median notochaetae in tufts, three per fascicle, all multiarticulate capillaries, articles short basally, poorly defined, longer medially and distally, each article with several rings (
<figureCitation box="[934,1038,553,578]" captionStart="FIGURE 39" captionStartId="76.[151,250,1707,1729]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,809,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@76.[172,1419,809,1664]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="FIGURE 39. Bradabyssa monnioti n. sp., holotype (MNHN IA-Type 1798). A. Dorsal view. B. Chaetiger 10, left parapodium, anterior view. C. Same, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. D. Same, basal, medial and distal neurochaetal regions. Scale bars. A: 0.5 mm, B: 90 µm, C – D: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041288/files/figure.png" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Fig. 39C</figureCitation>
); notochaetae (chaetiger 9) slightly longer than body width. Neurochaetae multiarticulate capillaries in chaetiger 1; aristate neurospines from chaetiger 2, short, longer from chaetiger 3, decrease in size posteriorly, 3 neurospines in anterior chaetigers, 
<quantity box="[1256,1299,625,650]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
median and posterior chaetigers, 
<quantity box="[393,468,661,686]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.81" metricValueMax="5.08" metricValueMin="2.54" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" unit="in" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2 in</quantity>
pre-pygidial segments. Neurospines with very short anchylose articles basally and medially, subdistally hyaline, slightly swollen, straight, aristae long, falcate (
<figureCitation box="[1010,1114,697,722]" captionStart="FIGURE 39" captionStartId="76.[151,250,1707,1729]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,809,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@76.[172,1419,809,1664]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="FIGURE 39. Bradabyssa monnioti n. sp., holotype (MNHN IA-Type 1798). A. Dorsal view. B. Chaetiger 10, left parapodium, anterior view. C. Same, basal, medial and distal notochaetal regions. D. Same, basal, medial and distal neurochaetal regions. Scale bars. A: 0.5 mm, B: 90 µm, C – D: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1041288/files/figure.png" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Fig. 39D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1437,151,758]" box="[199,1183,733,758]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Posterior end tapered into truncate cone; pygidium with anus terminal; anal cirri absent.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
