<subSubSection pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1437,1829,2034]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1829,1854]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2017" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" box="[325,568,1829,1854]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="monnioti" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[325,568,1829,1854]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Bradabyssa monnioti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[578,644,1829,1854]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[578,644,1829,1854]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
closely resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2017" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" box="[866,1031,1829,1854]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="kirkegaardi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[866,1031,1829,1854]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">B. kirkegaardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1041,1107,1829,1854]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1041,1107,1829,1854]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
because both are whitish in colour and their papillae have fine sediment particles adhering basally. They differ due to the relative homogeneity of the body wall surface and the relative size of notochaetal articles: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" box="[917,1048,1903,1926]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="monnioti">
<emphasis box="[917,1048,1903,1926]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">B. monnioti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a rugose body wall with about three transverse ridges per segment, and its notochaetae have long articles each with several annulations, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2017" box="[180,342,1973,1998]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Bradabyssa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="kirkegaardi">
<emphasis box="[180,342,1973,1998]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">B. kirkegaardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the body wall is homogeneous, smooth, without any transverse ridge, and notochaetae have long smooth articles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="77" pageNumber="78" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="77.[151,1437,151,285]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,151,176]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Etymology</emphasis>
. This species in named after the late Dr. Claude Monniot, well-known ascidian specialist, who was in charge of the biological program during the SAFARI cruises (Monniot 1984), during which this and other interesting polychaetes were collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
